body:
When I finish the "hook up the data model" bit of the react tutorial, I get an warning because the data model doesn't have a unique key. 

```
Each child in an array should have a unique "key" prop. Check the render method of CommentList. See http://fb.me/react-warning-keys for more information. react.js:9746
```

Maybe it's no big deal? If so, I'd be happy to do a pull request to have the docs let the user know to expect that error for now. Or if it is problematic, maybe another step could be added to account for the additional complexity? (Also entirely possible that I missed something obvious, but I've mainly been copy-pasting)

This is the tutorial:

http://facebook.github.io/react/docs/tutorial.html

And here is the code I have up to this point:

```
/** @jsx React.DOM */

// tutorial10.js
var CommentList = React.createClass({
  render: function() {
    var commentNodes = this.props.data.map(function (comment) {
      return (
        <Comment author={comment.author}>
          {comment.text}
        </Comment>
        );
    });
    return (
      <div className="commentList">
        {commentNodes}
      </div>
      );
  }
});

var CommentForm = React.createClass({
  render: function() {
    return (
      <div className="commentForm">
      Hello, world! I am a CommentForm.
      </div>
      );
  }
});

// tutorial3.js
var CommentBox = React.createClass({
  render: function() {
    return (
      <div className="commentBox">
        <h1>Comments</h1>
        <CommentList data={this.props.data} />
        <CommentForm />
      </div>
      );
  }
});

// tutorial5.js
var Comment = React.createClass({
  render: function() {
    return (
      <div className="comment">
        <h2 className="commentAuthor">
          {this.props.author}
        </h2>
        {this.props.children}
      </div>
      );
  }
});

// tutorial8.js
var data = [
  {author: "Pete Hunt", text: "This is one comment"},
  {author: "Jordan Walke", text: "This is *another* comment"}
];

React.renderComponent(
  <CommentBox data={data} />,
  document.getElementById('content')
);
```

Nothing special there, copy pasted from the examples.
